# TSDoc Best Practices

When creating or modifying TypeScript code, always add or update TSDoc for exported APIs.

## Requirements

- Add `/** ... */` TSDoc blocks for exported functions, classes, interfaces, types, enums, and hooks.
- Start with a short imperative summary line.
- Include `@param` for each non-trivial parameter (name + purpose).
- Include `@returns` when return type/value is meaningful.
- Include `@throws` when errors are intentionally thrown.
- Add `@example` for APIs that are easy to misuse or non-obvious.
- Keep docs accurate when signatures or behavior change.

## Style

- Describe behavior and intent, not implementation details.
- Keep comments concise and scannable.
- Use valid TSDoc tags and avoid ad-hoc formatting.
- Do not add redundant comments for private/internal code unless complexity warrants it.
